{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141013005218|629374808","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Sheila_Jackson_Lee","to":"Sheila Jackson Lee"}],"pages":{"479733":{"pageid":479733,"ns":0,"title":"Sheila Jackson Lee","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-11-20T05:14:09Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox congressman\n| name                = Sheila Jackson Lee\n| image               = SheilaJackson.JPG\n| imagesize           =\n| state               = [[Texas]]\n| district            = [[Texas's 18th congressional district|18th]]\n| term_start          = January 3, 1995\n| preceded            = [[Craig Washington]]\n| succeeded           = Incumbent\n| office2             = Member of the [[Houston City Council]] from the At-large #4 District\n| term_start2         = January 2, 1990\n| term_end2           = January 3, 1995\n| predecessor2        = [[Anthony Hall (Houston politician)|Anthony Hall]]\n| successor2          = [[John Peavy]]\n|birth_name=Sheila Jackson\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1950|01|12}}\n| birth_place         = [[Queens, New York]]\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| nationality         =\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse              = [[Elwyn C. Lee]]\n| relations           =\n| children            = 2\n| residence           = [[Houston]], [[Texas]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Yale University]]<br>[[University of Virginia|University of Virginia Law School]]\n| occupation          =\n| profession          = Attorney, Judge\n| religion            = [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]]\n| signature           =\n| website             = [http://jacksonlee.house.gov jacksonlee.house.gov]\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n\n'''Sheila Jackson Lee''' (born January 12, 1950) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TX|18}}, serving since 1995.  The district includes most of inner-city [[Houston, Texas|Houston]].  She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nJackson Lee graduated from [[Jamaica High School (New York City)|Jamaica High School]] in [[Queens]]. She earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[political science]] from [[Yale University]] in 1972, followed by a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from the [[University of Virginia School of Law]] in 1975.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacksonlee.house.gov/Biography/|title=Sheila Jackson Lee: Biography|publisher=House.gov|accessdate=September 14, 2010}}</ref> She is a member of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] sorority.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pride and comfort ; National black sorority 'gathers for the specific purpose of being selfless'|first=Stephen|last=Magagnini|work=Beaumont Enterprise|location=Beaumont, Tex.|date=January 1, 2008|page=B.1}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nJackson Lee made three unsuccessful attempts at local [[judge]]ships before becoming a municipal judge from 1987 to 1990.<ref name=Feldman>{{cite news|title=SHEILA JACKSON LEE GOES TO WASHINGTON|first=CLAUDIA |last=FELDMAN|work=Houston Chronicle|date=February 19, 1995|page=6}}</ref>\nJackson Lee, along with Sylvia Garcia, was appointed by then [[Mayor of Houston]] [[Kathy Whitmire]]. In 1989 she won the at-large position for a seat on the [[Houston City Council]], serving until 1994.<ref name=Feldman/> While on the city council, Jackson Lee helped pass a safety ordinance that required parents to keep their guns away from children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Council moves to keep guns away from kids|first=JAMES |last=ROBINSON|work=Houston Chronicle|date=April 23, 1992|page=1}}</ref> She also worked for expanded summer hours at city parks and recreation centers as a way to combat [[gang]] violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=FOR CONGRESS, DIST. 18/Recommending nomination of Sheila Jackson Lee|work=Houston Chronicle|date=February 13, 1994|page=2}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1994\nIn 1994, Jackson Lee challenged four-term incumbent U.S. Congressman [[Craig Washington]] in the Democratic [[primary election|primary]].<ref name=Feldman/>  Washington had come under fire for opposing several projects that would have benefited the Houston area.<ref name=\"dms\"/> Jackson Lee defeated Washington in a rout, taking 63% to Washington's 37%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=222684 |title=TX District 18 - D Primary Race - Mar 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref> The victory was [[tantamount to election]] in this heavily Democratic, black-majority district. In the general election, she defeated Republican nominee Jerry Burley 73%-24%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29125 |title=TX District 18 Race - Nov 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref>\n\n;1996-2008\nDuring this time period, Jackson Lee was never challenged in the Democratic primary. She won re-election during this time with at least 76% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1771 |title=Candidate - Sheila Jackson-Lee |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2010#District 18}}\nFor the first time in her congressional career, Jackson Lee was challenged in the Democratic primary; her opponents were Houston City Councilmember [[Jarvis Johnson]] and Sean Roberts. She defeated them 67%-28%-5%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=612081 |title=TX District 18 - D Primary Race - Mar 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that in October 2010 Jackson Lee was \u201casking the Department of Justice to investigate whether tea party groups are intimidating black and Hispanic voters in her district.\u201d She requested that Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] send poll monitors to make sure that a local group wasn't stopping people from voting.<ref name=\"Monitor Tea Party\">{{cite news|title=Sheila Jackson Lee wants DOJ to monitor tea partiers at polls|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1010/44331.html|newspaper=[[Politico]]|date=28 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nShe won the general election with 70% of the vote, the lowest winning percentage of her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=525764 |title=TX - District 18 Race - Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref>\n\n;2012\nIn 2012, Jackson Lee was not challenged in the Democratic primary and won the general election with 75% of the vote.<ref>http://www.texastribune.org/directory/districts/us-house/18/</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nPrior to the [[110th United States Congress|110th Congress]], Jackson Lee served on the [[United States House Committee on Science and Technology|House Science Committee]] and on the Subcommittee that oversees [[U.S. National Space Policy|space policy]] and [[NASA]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} She is a member of the [[Congressional Black Caucus]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Who's Who in the Congressional Black Caucus|last=Wright|first=James|work=Afro - American Red Star|location=Washington, D.C.|date=September 23, 1995|volume=104|issue=6|page=B1}}</ref> and a CBC whip.<ref name=\"dms\"/>\n\n===Worst Boss===\nIn 2011 she was reported to have one of the highest staff turnovers in Congress and to be one of the worst bosses. The Huffington Post and Houston Chronicle reported that she had gone through 11 chiefs of staff in 11 years.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\">http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/06/20/sheila-jackson-lee-chiefs-of-staff-tunrnover_n_880330.html</ref><ref>http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/politics/article/Jackson-Lee-and-Cuellar-see-heavy-turnover-in-1431222.php#ixzz1PpBk7JlD Heavy Turnover</ref> In 2011 she was named as one of the \"worst bosses in Washington\" by \"[[Daily Caller]]\" <ref>http://dailycaller.com/2011/03/02/congressional-bosses-from-hell-sheila-jackson-lee/ Bosses From Hell</ref>  The Huffington Post stated that \"Jackson Lee regularly appears on Washingtonian magazine's list of the \u201cBest and Worst of Congress\u201d as the \u201cmeanest\u201d member of House of Representatives.\" <ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/><ref>http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2013/01/report-sheila-jackson-lee-is-worst-boss-on-capitol-hill/#4095101=0 Houston Chronicle</ref> That reputation as the worst boss on Capital Hill continued;in 2012 Washingtonian again listed her as the meanest member of the House,<ref>http://www.washingtonian.com/articles/people/best-and-worst-of-congress-2012/indexp2.php</ref> a report in 2013 concluded that \"the veteran Texas Democrat had the highest turnover rate for all of Congress over the past decade.\" <ref>http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/jan/22/who-are-the-best-and-worst-bosses-on-capitol-hill/ Best and Worst Bosses</ref>\n\n===Foreign Policy===\nIn 2000, she favored permanently normalizing [[Trade policy|trade status]] for [[China]], arguing that it would aid both [[human rights]] and [[Economy of Houston|Houston's economy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Small firms to get help in exporting|work=Houston Chronicle|date=October 7, 2000|page=2}}</ref>\n\nJackson Lee traveled to the [[World Conference against Racism 2001|2001 World Conference against Racism]] in [[South Africa]], and has backed [[economic sanctions|sanctions]] against [[Sudan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=DELEGATION WATCH / Jackson Lee backs her vow on Darfur / Calls her arrest a statement on the war and genocide|first=SAMANTHA |last=LEVINE|work=Houston Chronicle|date=April 30, 2006|page=10|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/nation/3828625.html}}</ref> On April 28, 2006, Jackson Lee, along with four other members of Congress and six other activists, was arrested for disorderly conduct in front of [[Sudan]]'s [[embassy]] in Washington. They were protesting the role of Sudan's government in [[Darfur conflict|ethnic cleansing in Darfur]].<ref>Jim Doyle, [http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/04/28/MNG4RIH93T7.DTL Five members of Congress arrested over Sudan protest], ''San Francisco Chronicle'', April 28, 2006. Retrieved 25 September 2006.</ref>\n\nJackson Lee has urged better relations between the U.S. and [[Venezuela]], which she describes as a friendly nation. She said the U.S. should reconsider its ban on selling [[F-16]] fighter jets and spare parts to that country. The [[U.S. State Department]] bans such sales due to \"lack of support\" for counter-terrorist operations and Venezuela's relations with [[Iran]] and [[Cuba]].<ref>{{Wayback |date=20070225082446 |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/tx/4571152.html |title=\"Jackson Lee wants ban on fighter jets reconsidered\"}}. ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''. February 21, 2007</ref><ref>\"[http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4291743 Jackson Lee tries to smooth Chavez ties / Her Venezuela trip, she says, was an attempt to protect jobs here].\" ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''.</ref>\n\nIn July 2010 Jackson Lee said: \"Today, we have two Vietnams, side by side, North and South, exchanging and working. We may not agree with all that North Vietnam is doing, but they are living in peace. I would look for a better human rights record for North Vietnam, but they are living side by side.\u201d<ref name=\"Two Vietnams\">{{cite news|title=Sheila Jackson Lee Catches Flack for Citing \"Two Vietnams\"|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20010824-503544.html|newspaper=CBS News|date=16 July 2010|deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> It was noted that [[Vietnam]] had not been split for four decades.<ref name=\"North and South\">{{cite web|title=Sheila Jackson Lee says there are two Vietnams: North and South|url=http://www.politifact.com/texas/statements/2010/jul/21/sheila-jackson-lee/sheila-jackson-lee-says-there-are-two-vietnams-nor/|publisher=PolitiFact}}</ref><ref name=\"Rare Commodity\">{{cite news|title=Politicians Worthy Of Respect Are A Rare Commodity|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/henrymiller/2012/05/02/politicians-worthy-of-respect-are-a-rare-commodity/|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=15 August 2012|first=Henry I.|last=Miller}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nJackson Lee is active on immigration issues.<ref>Bill Swindell, \"[http://www.govexec.com/defense/2006/11/texas-democrat-gets-praise-for-immigration-efforts/23204/ Texas Democrat gets praise for immigration efforts]\", ''Government Executive'', 27 November 2006.</ref> She has proposed increasing border security and increasing opportunities for legalization among those living in the United States. She has opposed a guest worker program, saying that the idea of guest: \"connotate[s] `invite, come,' and, at the same time, it misleads because you ask people to come for a temporary job of three to six years and they have to leave if they don't have another job and I would think that they would not.\"<ref>Sheila Jackson Lee, \"[http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4817071 Illegal Immigration's Impact on the U.S. Economy]\", ''NPR'', 26 August 2005.</ref>\n\n===Accusations Against Tea Party===\nSpeaking in July 2010 at the NAACP national convention, Jackson Lee compared the Tea Party to the [[KKK]].<ref name=\"Tea Party and the Klan\">{{cite news|title=Sheila Jackson Lee on the Tea Party and the Klan|url=http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/07/sheila-Jackson-Lee-on-the-tea-party-and-the-klan/59888/|newspaper=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\n===Health Care===\nJackson Lee said in January 2011 that repealing the health care law would be in violation of the Constitution. She argued that the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] is constitutional under the Commerce Clause, and that repealing it would violate both the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth]] and the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendments]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Sheila Jackson Lee Says Repealing ObamaCare Violates Constitution|author= Phil Klein|url= http://spectator.org/blog/2011/01/18/shelia-jackson-lee-says-repeal|newspaper= American Spectator|date= 18 January 2011|accessdate= }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nation.foxnews.com/health-care/2011/01/19/sheila-jackson-lee-d-says-repealing-obamacare-unconstitutional | work=Fox News}}</ref>\n<ref>http://www.sfexaminer.com/sanfrancisco/rep-sheila-jackson-lee-d-texas-health-care-repeal-violates-the-fifth-amendment-or-something/Content?oid=2168065 SanFransisco Examiner</ref>\n\n===Al-Qaeda===\nAt a [[Homeland Security Committee]] hearing on radical Muslims in the US, held in March 2011, Jackson Lee said that [[Peter T. King|Peter King]]'s hearings were helping [[al-Qaeda]] and \u201cgoing the same route as Arizona.\u201d She complained that the hearings were scaring Muslim Americans and called them \u201can outrage.\u201d<ref name=\"Peter King says success\">{{cite news|title=Muslim 'radicalization' hearing a success, say Rep. Peter King, Republicans|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/11/news/la-pn-muslims-hearing-20110311|newspaper=LA Times|date=11 March 2011|first=James|last=Oliphant}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn September 27, 2013, Jackson Lee introduced the [[Essential Transportation Worker Identification Credential Assessment Act (H.R. 3202; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] to assess the effectiveness of the [[Transportation Worker Identification Credential]] (TWIC) program.<ref name=cbo3202>{{cite web|title=CBO - H.R. 3202|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45526|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref> The bill would require an independent assessment of how well the TWIC program improves security and reduces risks at the facilities and vessels it is responsible for.<ref name=WorkBoat1>{{cite web|title=Bill introduced to assess TWIC card|url=http://www.workboat.com/newsdetail.aspx?id=22235|website=WorkBoat.com|accessdate=29 July 2014|date=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Counterterrorism and Intelligence|Subcommittee on Counterterrorism and Intelligence]]\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation Security|Subcommittee on Transportation Security]] (Ranking Member)\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet|Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement|Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\nJackson Lee is or has been a member of a number of caucuses, including: the 9-11 Commission Caucus, the Building a Better America Caucus (BABAC), the [[Congressional Caucus on Global Road Safety]], and the [[Congressional Human Rights Caucus]]. Task forces in which she has participated include Children and Families, Homeland Security, Immigration, and Katrina. She has been the co-chair of the Congressional Algeria Caucus, the Congressional Pakistan Caucus, the Democratic Outreach Task Force, and the US-Afghan Caucus. Jackson Lee has also been a member of the House Democratic Steering Committee.\n\n===Personal life===\nJackson Lee moved to Houston after her husband, [[Elwyn C. Lee]], took a job at the [[University of Houston]]. Her husband now holds a dual position of Vice Chancellor and Vice President for Student Affairs of the [[University of Houston System]] and the [[University of Houston]], respectively.<ref name=bio/>\n\n===Space Program===\nIn 1997, while on a trip to the Mars Pathfinder operations center in California, Jackson Lee confused the planet Mars with Earth's own moon, asking whether the Pathfinder had succeeded in taking a picture of the flag planted on Mars by Neil Armstrong in 1969.<ref>http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/13/the-constitution-is-400-years-old-and-more-pearls-from-sheila-jackson-lee.html#sthash.BMtMS6JQ.dpuf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Houston|Biography|Government of the United States|Politics|African American}}\n* [[History of the African-Americans in Houston]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"dms\">{{cite news|work=Houston Press|title=What's Driving Miss Shelia?|author=Tim Fleck|date=20 February 1997|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/1997-02-20/news/what-s-driving-miss-shelia/Sheila/}}</ref>}}\nAlison Cook, [http://houston-press.com/1998-01-01/news/alison-cook-looks-back-at-1997-the-year-that-bit/4  Alison Cook looks back at 1997: The Year That Bit], Houston Press, May 2, 2007.\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.jacksonlee.house.gov/ Congresswoman Sheila Jackson Lee] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.sheilajacksonlee18.com/ Sheila Jackson Lee for U.S. Congress] \n*{{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federa